10) \u2013 Season 6\n# \"[[Counseling (The Office)|Counseling]]\" (September 30, 2010) \u2013 Season 7\n# \"[[Threat Level Midnight]]\" (February 17, 2011) \u2013 Season 7\n# \"[[The List (The Office)|The List]]\" (September 22, 2011) \u2013 Season 8\n# \"[[Free Family Portrait Studio]]\" (May 10, 2012) \u2013 Season 8\n[[Writers Guild of America Awards 2006#Comedy Series|Writers Guild of America Award for Comedy Series]] (2006)<br/> Nominated: [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#Comedy Series|Writers Guild of America Award for a Comedy Series]] (2005, 2007, 2008)<br/>Nominated: [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#New Series|Writers Guild of America Award for a New Series]] (2005)<br/>Nominated: [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#Episodic Comedy|Writers Guild of America Award for an Episodic Comedy]] (2005, 2007)\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''{{sortname|The|Mindy Project}}''\n| 2 episodes\n|}\n\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Roles as a director\n! Year\n! Title\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Office|The Office (U.S. TV series)}}'' \u2013 ''[[Blackmail (webisodes)|Blackmail]]'' webisode series\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''The Office'' \u2013 \"[[Scott's Tots]]\"\n| aired 12/03/09\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 2011\n| ''The Office'' \u2013 \"[[The Seminar]]\"\n| aired 01/27/11\n|-\n| ''The Office'' \u2013 \"[[The List (The Office)|The List]]\"\n| aired 09/22/11\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''The Office'' \u2013 \"[[Trivia (The Office)|Trivia]]\"\n| aired 01/12/12\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' \u2013 \"Mindy's Minute\"\n| aired 02/19/13\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''The Mindy Project'' \u2013 \"Santa Fe\"\n| aired 04/09/13\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ List of awards and nominations\n! Year\n! Group\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan = \"3\" | 2005\n| rowspan = \"3\" | [[Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#New Series|New Series]]\n| rowspan = \"14\" | ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#Episodic Comedy|Episodic Comedy]] \u2013 for episode \"[[Diversity Day (The Office episode)|Diversity Day]]\"\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2005#Comedy Series|Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | 2006\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2006#Comedy Series|Comedy Series]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan = \"4\" | 2007\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]<ref>Andrew Krukowski, [http://www.tvweek.com/news/2008/01/screen_actors_guild_honors_its.php \"'Sopranos,' 'The Office' Win SAG Ensemble Awards,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904085527/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2008/01/screen_actors_guild_honors_its.php |date=September 4, 2009 }} ''[[TVWeek]]'', January 27, 2008.</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" | [[Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2007#Episodic Comedy|Episodic Comedy]] \u2013 for episode \"[[Local Ad]]\"\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2007#Comedy Series|Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan = \"3\" | 2008\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards]]\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2008#Comedy Series|Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan = \"1\" | 2009\n| [[Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series#2000s|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|B.J. Novak}}\n{{externalvideo\n| align  = right\n| width  = 350px\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WNbVSNXm4iw Joey Fatone interviews Novak at the 14th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards (2008)]\n}}\n*[https://www.npr.org/blogs/bryantpark/2008/05/the_offices_bj_novak_uncut.html \"The Office's BJ Novak: Uncut\"], an NPR interview from May 2008\n* {{IMDb name|1145983|B. J. Novak}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVComedy 2000\u20132009}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novak, B. J.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Actors from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American comedy writers]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Harvard Lampoon alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish male comedians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Newton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hasty Pudding alumni]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Newton South High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|American actor, writer, and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = B. J. Novak\n|image       = B.J. Novak, Actor.jpg\n|caption     = Novak at SF Sketch Fest 2008\n|birth_name  = Benjamin Joseph Manaly Novak\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1979|7|31|mf=y}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoys |first1=Matt|last2=Brooks|first2=Mel |date=2013 |title=Comic Genius: Portraits of Funny People |url= |location= |publisher=[[Chronicle Books]] |page=194 |isbn=978-1452131955 |author-link= }}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Newton, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|alma_mater  = [[Harvard University]]\n|father = [[William Novak]]\n|relatives = [[Jesse Novak]] (brother)\n|occupation  = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian|director|}}\n|yearsactive = 2001\u2013present}}\n\n'''Benjamin Joseph Manaly Novak'''<ref>{{cite web|title=B.J. Novak|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|url=https://tvguide.com/celebrities/bj-novak/193427/|access-date=December 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215173010/https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/bj-novak/193427/|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> (born July 31, 1979) is an American actor, writer, comedian, and director. Novak was one of the writers and [[executive producer]]s of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' (2005\u20132013), in which he also played [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]].\n\n==Early life==\nNovak was born July 31, 1979, in [[Newton, Massachusetts]]. His parents are Linda (n\u00e9e {{Proper name|Manaly}}) and author [[William Novak]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Courtney Hollands|title=Molly Goodson has stars in her eyes \u2013 and on her blog|url=https://www.boston.com/lifestyle/fashion/articles/2007/12/20/shes_got_stars_in_her_eyes___and_on_her_blog|work=The Boston Globe|date=December 20, 2007|accessdate=March 6, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103180111/http://www.boston.com/lifestyle/fashion/articles/2007/12/20/shes_got_stars_in_her_eyes___and_on_her_blog/|archive-date=November 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Berman|first=Alyssa R.|author2=Beborah B. Doroshow|title=BJs Bring a Full House to Sanders|publisher=Harvard Crimson|date=May 14, 2001|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=104390|accessdate=August 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903131810/http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=104390|archive-date=September 3, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Novak|first=William|title=The Big Book of Jewish Humor|publisher=Collins|year=2006|page=vii|isbn=978-0-06-113813-3}}</ref> Novak's family is [[Jewish]]. His father co-edited ''The Big Book of Jewish Humor'', and has [[ghostwriter|ghostwritten]] memoirs for [[Nancy Reagan]], [[Lee Iacocca]], [[Magic Johnson]], and others; his parents also established a Jewish matchmaking service.<ref>{{cite news|last=Getlin|first=John|title=Ghost to the Stars \u2013 William Novak Is the Invisible Writer Behind Memoirs by Lee Iacocca, Nancy Reagan and\u2014Soon\u2014Magic Johnson|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=September 17, 1992|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-09-17/news/vw-968_1_william-novak|accessdate=August 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324134756/http://articles.latimes.com/1992-09-17/news/vw-968_1_william-novak|archive-date=March 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Uriel Heilman |title=Better than Pork, Isn't it? Jewish Joke Book turns 25 |url=http://jta.org/news/article/2006/11/19/14678/Betterthanp |work=JTA |date=November 19, 2006 |accessdate=March 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904043801/http://jta.org/news/article/2006/11/19/14678/Betterthanp |archivedate=September 4, 2009 |df= }}</ref> Novak has two younger brothers, [[Jesse Novak|Jesse]], a composer, and Lev. He attended [[Solomon Schechter Day School of Greater Boston]] for elementary school and middle school.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Class Notes-Solomon Schechter Day School|url=http://www.ssdsboston.org/alumni/class-notes|website=www.ssdsboston.org|access-date=January 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127100559/http://www.ssdsboston.org/alumni/class-notes|archive-date=January 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe went to [[Camp Ramah in New England]] for a couple of summers when he was a teenager.\n\nHe attended [[Newton South High School]] with future [[The Office (U.S. TV series)|'' The Office'']] costar [[John Krasinski]],<ref name=\"BG\">{{cite news|author=Christopher Muther|title=Class reunion|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2005/12/06/class_reunion|work=The Boston Globe|date=December 6, 2005|accessdate=March 6, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224164456/http://boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2005/12/06/class_reunion|archivedate=February 24, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and they graduated in 1997.<ref name=\"BG\" /> Novak graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 2001, where he was a member of the ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]'' and the [[Hasty Pudding Club]]. He majored in English and Spanish literature, and wrote his honors thesis on the films of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] ''[[Hamlet]]''.<ref name=imdb />\n\nAside from the ''Lampoon'', he occasionally staged and performed in a variety show called ''The B.J. Show'' with fellow Harvard student [[B. J. Averell]].<ref name=\"BG\" />\n\n==Career==\nFollowing his graduation from Harvard, he moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and began working in clubs as a comedian. His first live stand-up performance took place at the [[Hollywood]] Youth Hostel on October 10, 2001.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} He was named one of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety's]]'' \"Ten Comedians To Watch\" in 2003.<ref name=\"CC\">{{cite web|title=B.J. Novak: Videos, Jokes, Tour Dates, Biography and more|url=http://www.comedycentral.com/comedians/browse/n/bj_novak.jhtml|work=Jokes.com|publisher=ComedyCentral|year=2009|accessdate=March 11, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020040317/http://www.comedycentral.com/comedians/browse/n/bj_novak.jhtml |archivedate=October 20, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNovak was a writer for the short-lived [[The WB Television Network|The WB]] sitcom ''[[Raising Dad]]''.<ref name=BG /> He performed on [[Comedy Central]]'s ''[[Premium Blend]]'' and on ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]]''.<ref name=imdb /><ref name=CC />\n\nNovak's television acting career began on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Punk'd]]''.<ref name=\"BG\" /> He was the lead accomplice to [[Ashton Kutcher]] on the show's second season in 2003, playing pranks on [[Hilary Duff]], [[Rachael Leigh Cook]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], and [[M\u00fda]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}[[File:Bjnovak crop.jpg|thumb|Novak in June 2007|264x264px]]\n\n===''The Office''===\n{{expand section|date=January 2017}}\nAfter hearing Novak's opening joke at a comedy club, executive producer [[Greg Daniels]] decided he \"wanted to do something with him\";<ref name=\"BG\" /> Novak was subsequently cast as [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]].\n\nBj Plays a character who goes through ups and downs throughout his work career and has an on off relationship with Kelly Kapoor (Mindy Kaling)\n\nNovak was not only a cast member on the show but a producer and writer. He along with Mindy Kaling, Greg Daniels, Michael Schur, and Paul Lieberstein were the original writers for the show. He is credited with writing fifteen episodes during the show's duration including the Writer's Guild of America nominated episodes \"Diversity Day\" and \"Local Ad\".\n\nOn July 21, 2010, news reports indicated Novak had signed a contract to remain with the show for its seventh and eighth seasons; under the new terms, he would be made an executive producer midway through Season 7 and direct two episodes of the show. In a June 2009 interview with ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', Novak spoke about sharing the success of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' with his [[Newton South High School]] classmate [[John Krasinski]]:<ref>David Hiltbrand, [http://articles.philly.com/2009-06-11/news/25286441_1_novak-triple-threat-joke \"B.J. Novak gives at 'The Office' and out of it\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083828/http://articles.philly.com/2009-06-11/news/25286441_1_novak-triple-threat-joke |date=March 4, 2016 }}, ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', June 11, 2009.</ref><blockquote>\"Sometimes when this feels too good to be true, I think that if this were all a dream, that would be what should have tipped me off. I'd wake up saying, \"I was in this incredible TV show and it was a big hit and the star was John [Krasinski] from high school. Isn't that weird?\"</blockquote>\n\n===Post ''The Office'' career===\nNovak has appeared in the films ''[[Unaccompanied Minors]]'', ''[[Reign Over Me]]'', ''[[The Internship]]'', ''[[Knocked Up]]'', ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'', and ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]''.\n\nHe has had supporting roles in [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Inglourious Basterds]]'' (2009), [[John Lee Hancock]]'s ''[[Saving Mr. Banks]]'' (2013), and ''[[The Founder]]'' (2016).\n\nHe has starred in episodes of ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]'', ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', and ''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]''.<ref name=imdb>{{IMDb name|nm1145983}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BJNovak2013.jpeg|thumb|right|Novak in September 2013]]\n\n===Book deal===\nOn April 11, 2013, publishing house [[Alfred A. Knopf]] announced it had signed a seven-figure, two-book deal with Novak, with the first book slated to be a fictional collection of [[Woody Allen]]-like stories.<ref>Julie Bosman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/12/business/media/bj-novak-actor-and-writer-signs-two-book-deal.html?_r=1& \"B.J. Novak, Actor and Writer, Signs Two-Book Deal\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624210007/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/12/business/media/bj-novak-actor-and-writer-signs-two-book-deal.html?_r=1& |date=June 24, 2017 }}, nytimes.com, April 12, 2013; accessed September 21, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2014 a book of 22 stories, ''One More Thing: Stories and Other Stories'', was published and spent 6 weeks on the NYT Hardcover Fiction Bestsellers List.<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Sellers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-03-30/hardcover-fiction/list.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=November 30, 2014|date=March 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202210535/http://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-03-30/hardcover-fiction/list.html|archive-date=December 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Novak also signed a deal with Penguin's children's books label and wrote  ''The Book With No Pictures'', which was released in September 2014 and has spent four full years on the New York Times Picture Books list, with 34 weeks charting as the #1 seller in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Towers|first1=Andrea|title=On the Books: B.J. Novak lands children's book deal|url=http://shelf-life.ew.com/2014/01/22/on-the-books-b-j-novak-lands-childrens-book-deal/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=November 30, 2014|date=January 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205123518/http://shelf-life.ew.com/2014/01/22/on-the-books-b-j-novak-lands-childrens-book-deal/|archive-date=December 5, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, it was announced that Novak and [[Mindy Kaling]] had signed a book deal worth a reported $7.5 million to write about their long friendship and former relationship, though Kaling said in an interview that the book would \"not be a tell-all.\"\n\n=== The List App ===\nOn October 14, 2015 Novak released an Apple [[iOS app]] along with co-founder Dev Flaherty called The List App.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/article/2015/10/14/bj-novak-list-app/|title=B.J. Novak introduces new app for people who 'just love lists'|work=EW.com|access-date=January 13, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113150335/http://ew.com/article/2015/10/14/bj-novak-list-app/|archive-date=January 13, 2018|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> The app has since been nominated for a [[2016 Webby Awards|Webby Award]] (losing in its category to [[Beme]] and [[Pocket (application)|Pocket]]) and in May 2016 rebranded as 'li.st' and became available on the Android platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/09/bj-novaks-the-list-app-rebrands-to-li-st-arrives-on-android/|title=B.J. Novak's \"The List App\" rebrands to li.st, arrives on Android|last=Perez|first=Sarah|work=TechCrunch|access-date=January 13, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113093422/https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/09/bj-novaks-the-list-app-rebrands-to-li-st-arrives-on-android/|archive-date=January 13, 2018|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the app was shut down, citing that the growth wasn't enough to sustain the current product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commaful.com/play/bestlistapp/list-app-shuts-down-the-list-app-by-bj-novak/|title=List App Shuts Down App, Moves On To New Project|last=|first=|date=|website=Commaful|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002022043/https://commaful.com/play/bestlistapp/list-app-shuts-down-the-list-app-by-bj-novak/|archive-date=October 2, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNovak has a close friendship with [[Mindy Kaling]], whom he met through writing for ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. The two dated on and off while writing and acting on the show, sometimes mirroring the on-again, off-again nature of the relationship between their respective characters [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan Howard]] and [[Kelly Kapoor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/summeranne/mindy-kaling-and-bj-novak-sitting-in-a-tree|title=33 Times Mindy Kaling And B.J. Novak's Best Friendship Killed You In The Heart|first=Summer Anne|last=Burton|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=May 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011041146/https://www.buzzfeed.com/summeranne/mindy-kaling-and-bj-novak-sitting-in-a-tree|archive-date=October 11, 2016|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> He served as a consulting producer for Season 1 of ''[[The Mindy Project]]'',<ref>[http://ohnotheydidnt.livejournal.com/75080922.html \"B.J. Novak on his 'Mindy Project' arc, being BFF with Mindy Kaling, and returning to 'The Office'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203114624/http://ohnotheydidnt.livejournal.com/75080922.html |date=February 3, 2013 }}, ohnotheydidnt.livejournal.com, January 29, 2013.</ref> and has appeared on the show several times, though his formal producing role ended after the first season.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.glamour.com/story/bj-novak-the-mindy-project | title=B.J. Novak on His Relationship with Mindy Kaling and Returning to the Mindy Project | access-date=February 3, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204000027/https://www.glamour.com/story/bj-novak-the-mindy-project | archive-date=February 4, 2018 | url-status=live | df= }}</ref> Novak is the godfather of Kaling's daughter, Katherine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/parents/mindy-kaling-reveals-bj-novak-godfather-to-her-daughter/|title=Mindy Kaling Reveals B.J. Novak Is Godfather to Her 16-Month-Old Daughter: He's 'Family Now'|date=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |author=Novak, B. J. |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The book with no pictures |location= |year=2014 |<!--isbn=9780803741713-->}}\n*{{cite book |author=Novak, B. J. |authorlink= |authormask=1 |title=One more thing : stories and other stories |location= |year=2014 |<!--isbn=9780385351836-->}}\n*{{cite book |author=Novak, B. J. |authorlink= |authormask= |title=The alphabet book with no pictures |location= |year=2017 |<!--isbn=9780803741713-->}